, northern Middle English <i>law</i> (from Old English <i>hlāw</i>, which generally became <i>low</i> in the south and <i>law</i> in the north). Compare   Lowe   and   Lew  .","Chinese: variant Romanization of the surname 羅, based on its Cantonese pronunciation, see   Luo   1."]},{"name":"Lowe","meanings":["English and Scottish: variant of   Low  .","German (<b>Löwe</b>) and Danish (<b>Løwe</b>): from Middle High German <i>lēwe</i>, <i>löuwe</i> ‘lion’, hence a nickname for a brave or regal person. In some cases the surname may have been a topographic or habitational name referring to a house or inn distinguished by the sign of a lion. It is also found in Sweden. Compare   Loewe   1,   Lau  ,   Lave  , and   Lurvey  .","Jewish (Ashkenazic; <b>Löwe</b>): artificial name from German <i>Löwe</i> ‘lion’."]},{"name":"Leavitt","meanings":["English:","(of Norman origin): nickname from Anglo-Norman French <i>leuet</i> ‘wolf cub’ (see   Low   3).","habitational name from any of various places in Normandy called Livet. All are of obscure, presumably Gaulish, etymology."]}]},{"name":"Margery","type":"FIRST","attribution":"Dictionary of First Names © Patrick Hanks and Flavia Hodges 1990, 2003, 2006.","meanings":["The usual medieval vernacular form of   Margaret   (now also commonly spelled   Marjorie  ). This form of the name is preserved in the nursery rhyme ‘See-saw, Margery Daw’."],"variants":[]}],"lifeSummary":"When Mrs Margery Low was born in 1194, in Hatch, Somerset, England, United Kingdom, her father, William LeMegre, was 28 and her mother, Mrs William LeMegre, was 28. She had at least 1 daughter with Sir John de Low."},"et":{"1194–":"1194–Surnud","1194–Female":"1194–Surnud","1188–1288":"1188–1288","1246–1310":"1246–1310","1167–Male":"1167–Surnud","1167–Female":"1167–Surnud","1246":"1246","1167":"1167","1310":"1310","1288":"1288","1188":"1188","1194":"1194","Hatch, Somerset, England":"Hatch, Somerset, Inglismaa, United Kingdom"},"fi":{"1194–":"1194–Kuollut","1194–Female